Methods for Character Type
These methods return True if all characters in the string meet the condition and the string is not empty;
otherwise, they return False. To check a single character, you can iterate through the string or access it by index. 

isalnum(): Checks if all characters are alphanumeric (letters or numbers).
isalpha(): Checks if all characters are alphabetic (letters only).
isdigit(): Checks if all characters are digits (0-9).
isnumeric(): A broader check for numeric characters, including digits, Unicode exponents, and some fractions.
isdecimal(): Checks for characters that are decimals (a subset of isdigit() and isnumeric()).
islower() / isupper(): Checks if all alphabetic characters are in lowercase or uppercase, respectively.
isspace(): Checks if all characters are whitespace characters.
isprintable(): Checks if all characters are printable.
istitle(): Checks if the string follows the rules of a title (first letter of each word is uppercase, rest are lowercase)



------------------------------------------
lower(): Converts all characters in the string to lowercase
"HELLO World".lower() # Output: "hello world"

upper(): Converts all characters in the string to uppercase.
"Hello World".upper() # Output: "HELLO WORLD"

capitalize(): Converts the first character of the string to uppercase and the rest to lowercase.
"hello world".capitalize() # Output: "Hello world"

title(): Converts the first character of each word to uppercase
"he's name is dan".title() # Output: "He'S Name Is Dan"

swapcase(): Swaps the case of all characters (uppercase becomes lowercase, and vice versa).
"Hello World".swapcase() # Output: "hELLO wORLD"

find(substring): Searches for the first occurrence of the substring and returns its lowest index.
If not found, it returns -1.
"Hello world".find("o") # Output: 4

index(substring): Similar to find(), but raises a ValueError if the substring is not found.

replace(old, new): Replaces all occurrences of the old substring with the new substring.
"hello world".replace("world", "Python") # Output: "hello Python"

count(substring): Returns the number of times a specified substring occurs in the string.
"Abracadabra".count("a") # Output: 4

startswith(prefix): Returns True if the string starts with the specified prefix, otherwise False.

endswith(suffix): Returns True if the string ends with the specified suffix, otherwise False.
---------------------------------------------------------------
Whitespace and Joining/Splitting 
strip(): Removes any leading and trailing whitespace (or other specified characters)
" Hello World ".strip() # Output: "Hello World"

split(delimiter): Splits the string into a list of substrings based on the delimiter. 
If no delimiter is provided, it splits on any whitespace.
"one two three".split() # Output: ['one', 'two', 'three']

join(iterable): Joins the elements of an iterable (e.g., a list of strings)
into a single string using the string itself as the separator.
"-".join(["2025", "05", "08"]) # Output: "2025-05-08"




